The missing number correlation heatmap generated below shows the measure of nullity correlation between the different attributes. The attributes that have a perfect positive nullity correlation of 1 between two features indicate that the first and second features have missing values while -1 indicates one feature has missing values while the other doesnt.¶

In [148]:
msno.heatmap(df1[missingdata_df], figsize=(10,10))
#This map describes the degree of nullity relationship between the different features. 
#The range of this nullity correlation is from -1 to 1 (-1 ≤ R ≤ 1). Features with no missing value are excluded in the heatmap. 
#If the nullity correlation is very close to zero (-0.05 < R < 0.05), no value will be displayed. 
#Also, a perfect positive nullity correlation (R=1) indicates when the first feature and the second feature both have corresponding missing values 
#while a perfect negative nullity correlation (R=-1)means that one of the features is missing and the second is not missing.

The plot below shows the decomposition of the discharge temp attribute from the AHU data into trend, seasonal and residual components. From the trend plot, it is seen that the discharge temperature has a significant drop during the month of December. The decomposition frequency is taken as 7 days ie 1 week. The Observed plot is from the original data, seasonal is the repetition within the frequency, trend shows the pattern/trend while residual is everything that is not described by seasonal or trend.¶

In [135]:
#weekly wise
#Evaluation of the TimeSeries Decomposition
#We are taking the decomposition frequency as 7 days
#Seasonal Decomposition of the data: Observed is the original data, seasonal is the repetition within freq,
#trend is the trend and residual is everything, which is not described by seasonal+trend

import statsmodels.api as sm
decompfreq = 7*24
res = sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose(df2.Discharge_Temp.interpolate(),
 freq=decompfreq, model='additive')
resplot = res.plot()
#result = seasonal_decompose(series, model='additive', frequency = )
